{"title_page": "Vocational panel", "text_new": "A '''vocational panel''' ({{lang-ga|rolla gairm bheatha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Olltoghch\u00e1n an tSeanaid, 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/ga/election-results/seanad-general-election-2020/ |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=ga |date=3 April 2020 |quote=Foilseofar na tortha\u00ed comhairimh is d\u00e9ana\u00ed do na c\u00faig rolla gairm bheatha anseo d\u00edreach tar \u00e9is toradh gach comhairimh a fh\u00f3gairt.}}</ref>) is any of five lists of candidates from which are elected a total of 43 of the 60{{#tag:ref|Of the other 17 senators, 6 are elected from [[University constituency|university constituencies]] and [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|11 are appointed]] by the [[Taoiseach]] ([[prime minister]]).|group=\"n\"}} senators in [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], the [[upper house]] of the [[Oireachtas]] ([[parliament]]) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. Each panel corresponds to a grouping of \"interests and services\" ([[profession]]s or [[vocation]]s) of which candidates are required to have \"knowledge and practical experience\". The panels are nominated partly by Oireachtas members and partly by vocational organisations. From each panel, between five and eleven senators are [[Indirect election|elected indirectly]], by Oireachtas members and [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|local councillors]], using the [[single transferable vote]]. The broad requirements are specified by Article 18 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and the implementation details by [[acts of the Oireachtas]], principally the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, and associated [[statutory instrument]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement, Amendments, SIs made under the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/isbc/1947_42.html |website=Irish Statute Book |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interests and services, and subpanels==\nArticle 18.7.1\u00b0 of the Constitution defines the five panels and specifies that each shall elect between five and eleven senators. The 1947 act defines the numbers of senators to be elected from each of the panels, and also provides for the division of each panel into two sub-panels: the nominating bodies sub-panel and the Oireachtas sub-panel, with a minimum number from each sub-panel. The number of nominations any one body can make depends on both the number of bodies registered for the panel, and the number of senators elected from it.<ref name=\"maxperbody\"/>\t \n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Senate vocational panels\n!rowspan=2|Panel\n!colspan=2|Senators\n!colspan=2|Nominating bodies (as of 2020)\n!rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|\"Interests and services\" represented<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/3/enacted/en/html#sec3 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.3]</ref>\n|-\n!Total  !!Min. per<br/>sub-panel\n!Number<ref>{{cite web |title=Register of Nominating Bodies as revised at the annual revision and signed by the Seanad Returning Officer in pursuance of section 19 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended. |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/nominatingBodies/seanad/2019/2019-07-24_register-of-nominating-bodies-2019_en.pdf |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n!Max nominees<br/>per body<ref name=\"maxperbody\">[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/7/enacted/en/html s.26(2) of the 1947 act as amended by s.7 of the 1954 act]</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Administrative Panel|Administrative]]\n| 7  || 3\n| 20 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Public administration and social services, including voluntary social activities\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Agricultural Panel|Agricultural]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 10 || 2\n|align=\"left\"| \"Agriculture and allied interests, and fisheries\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cultural and Educational Panel|Cultural and Educational]]\n| 5  || 2\n| 34 || 1 \n|align=\"left\"| \"The national language {{bracket|i.e. [[Irish language|Irish]]}} and culture, literature, art, education\" and \"such [[profession]]al interests as may be defined by law\", namely \"law\" and \"medicine, including surgery, dentistry, veterinary medicine, and pharmaceutical chemistry\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Industrial and Commercial Panel|Industrial and Commercial]]\n| 9  || 3\n| 47 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Industry and commerce, including banking, finance, accountancy, engineering, and architecture\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Labour Panel|Labour]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 2  || 7\n|align=\"left\"| \"Labour, whether [[trade union|organised]] or unorganised\"\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Total\n| 43  || \u2014\n| 113 || \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Nominations==\nCandidates must be Irish citizens over the age of 21.  They can be nominated in two ways: by four members of Oireachtas (the new D\u00e1il or the outgoing Seanad) or by a \"nominating body\", to form respectively the Oireachtas (\"inside\") subpanel and Nominating bodies (\"outside\") subpanel.\n\n===Nominating bodies===\nA nominating body for a panel is a organisation whose work or members relates to one or more of the interests on the panel; for example, the [[Irish Congress of Trade Unions]] (ICTU) can nominate in the Labour panel, and the [[Royal Irish Academy]] in the Cultural and Education panel. Bodies must be [[non-profit]] within minimum [[governance]] standards.<ref name=\"act1947s8\">[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/8/enacted/en/html#sec8 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, s.8]</ref> The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad maintains the register of nominating bodies, published annually in ''[[Iris Oifigi\u00fail]]''. Bodies refused registration can appeal to a board comprising the [[Ceann Comhairle]] and [[Cathaoirleach]], their deputies, and a senior judge. A body cannot be registered on two panels;<ref name=\"act1947s8\"/> thus the [[Royal Dublin Society]] is on the Agricultural panel but not the Cultural and Educational panel. A body and an affiliate may not be registered on the same panel, but may be registered on different ones; for example the ICTU-affiliated [[Irish National Teachers' Organisation]] (INTO) is on the Cultural and Educational panel.\n\n===Knowledge and practical experience===\nThere is no statutory definition of what constitutes a sufficient degree of \"knowledge and practical experience\" of an interest or service to be eligible for nomination to the relevant panel.<ref name=\"groves2018\">{{cite web |last1=Groves |first1=Martin |title=Third Meeting |nopp=y |url=https://assets.gov.ie/3593/301118151408-17c7dc50bc56471da257862ca08cdf67.pdf#page=5 |editor=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |accessdate=5 April 2020 |page=Appendix: Presentation |date=12 June 2018}}</ref> The question is decided by the [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad, but may be be referred by him, or appealed by the candidate, to a judge of the [[High Court]] appointed as \"judicial referee\".<ref name=\"judicialreferee\">1947 act \u00a7\u00a736(2)(b)(ii), 38</ref> No further [[judicial review]] is permitted.<ref name=\"judicialreferee\"/> In 2018 clerk Martin Groves said that \"legislative guidelines would be of assistance to the returning officer and, I am sure, to candidates also\".<ref name=\"groves2018\"/> Before the [[Members of the 12th Seanad|1969 Seanad election]], outgoing Labour-panel senators [[John Ormonde]] and [[S\u00e9amus Dolan]] sought a pre-emptive High Court declaration that they were qualified, being members of a union (the INTO) affiliated to the ICTU.<ref name=\"it19690709\">{{cite news |title=Outgoing Senators Seek Declaration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0709/Pg011.html#Ar01100 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=9 July 1969 |page=11}}</ref> The Seanad clerk, Se\u00e1n MacGabhann, argued that as the INTO was itself a nominating body on the Cultural and Educational Panel, that was the panel on which they would be qualified.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> Justice [[Denis Pringle]] ruling in favour the plaintiffs, stated that it did not matter if they were better qualified for a different panel, and that, as regards the Labour Panel, while merely being in a union was insufficient, a candidate did not require \"specialised\" knowledge, and the plaintiff's testimony had established their qualifications.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senators win in election action|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0710/Pg007.html#Ar00704 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=10 July 1969 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=\"groves2018\"/> MacGabhann commented that, while an application form with detailed evidence similar to the plaintiffs' testimony might have satisfied him, a form simply making a bare assertion of knowledge and practical experience would not.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> In 2014, [[Fine Gael]] minister [[Heather Humphreys]] nominated John McNulty to the board of the [[Irish Museum of Modern Art]] (IMMA) shortly before Fine Gael nominated him to [[Gerard Craughwell#John McNulty|a by-election]] on the Oireachtas subpanel of the Cultural and Educational Panel. The IMMA nomination was seen as an attempt to bolster McNulty's tenuous qualifications, and the ensuing controversy impelled him to withdraw his candidacy.{{#tag:ref|His name remained from the ballot paper, but he urged electors not to vote for him.<ref name=\"mcgee2014/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=\"mcgee2014\">{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=Harry |title=Why is the John McNulty affair so important? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/why-is-the-john-mcnulty-affair-so-important-1.1951624 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=4 October 2014 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[2020 Seanad election]], Paul Hayes was excluded from the Agricultural panel on the basis that, although he had the required \"knowledge\" of fishing, he lacked \"practical experience\"; Hayes suggested that with more time he could have supplied sufficient documentation to support his case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Mahony |first1=Kieran |title=Hayes disappointed as Seanad nomination bids fail |url=https://www.southernstar.ie/news/hayes-disappointed-as-seanad-nomination-bids-fail-4202457 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Southern Star |date=25 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===<!-- [[Completion of panels]] redirects here-->Completion of panels===\nThe \"completion of panels\" occurs in public on a specified date after nominations close, when the clerk of the Seanad, assisted by the judicial referee, excludes invalid nomination papers and unqualified nominees, and allows candidates nominated on multiple panels or subpanels to select which one to go forward on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.36 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/36/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> This creates a list of provisional subpanels. The minimum number of nominees for each subpanel is two plus the maximum number to be elected from the subpanel. If there are too few candidates on a provisional subpanel, the [[Taoiseach]] must nominate extra candidates to complete the panel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.37 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/37/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[21st Seanad|1997 Seanad election]], [[Bertie Ahern]] was obliged to nominate four candidates across three Oireachtas sub-panels, none of whom polled well in the ensuing election.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Coakley |first1=John |last2=Manning |first2=Maurice |editor-last1=Marsh |editor-first1=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 1997 |chapter=The Senate Elections |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-96854-9 |page=203 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwDFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA203 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|appointments directly to the Seanad]] must be by a Taoiseach elected after a [[D\u00e1il election results|D\u00e1il general election]], nomination of candidates to complete a panel may be by an ''acting'' Taoiseach. For example, in 2020 [[Leo Varadkar]] was acting Taoiseach after [[2020 Irish general election|the D\u00e1il election]]; in [[2020 Irish Seanad election|the ensuing Seanad election]], Oireachtas members only nominated eight candidates to their subpanel of the Labour panel, so Varadkar nominated one more to bring the total up to the minimum of nine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panels of candidates prepared by the Seanad Returning Officer pursuant to Section 43 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954. |journal=Iris Oifigi\u00fail |date=10 March 2020 |issue=20A [Supplement] |page=6 |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/electoralRoll/seanad/2020/2020-03-10_seanad-general-election-2020-panels-of-candidates_en.pdf#page=6}}; {{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=FG\u2019s Mary Seery Kearney added to ticket to contest Seanad election |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fg-s-mary-seery-kearney-added-to-ticket-to-contest-seanad-election-1.4198771 |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voting==\nIn all panel elections [[postal voting]] is used. The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad is the [[returning officer]] of the count, during which each ballot is given the value of 1,000 to aid the transfer of fractions of votes. The [[electoral college]] is the same for all of the vocational panels but varies between general and [[by-election]]s. \n\nAt a Seanad general election the voters are members of [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|city and county councils]], the newly elected D\u00e1il and the outgoing Seanad; {{as of|2020|lc=y}} these number 949, 160, and 60 respectively, discounting any vacancies.{{#tag:ref|Typically, some local councillors and members of the old Seanad will have just been elected to the new D\u00e1il, vacating their former seats. In the case of a senator appointed by a Taoiseach, the outgoing acting Taoiseach will nominate a replacement in time for the panel election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=Former Labour TDs to compete for Seanad seats Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in in competition with outgoing senators for nomination |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/former-labour-tds-to-compete-for-seanad-seats-1.2571697 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> Typically, local councils likewise co-opt replacements in time,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Rachel |title=Rush to fill vacant seats created by councillors elected to D\u00e1il |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2016/0314/Pg002.html#Ar00203 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irush Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> but no by-elections are held to replace outgoing panel or university senators.  Before the 2003 abolition of the [[dual mandate]], one could be both an Oireachtas member and a local councillor, but would only get one vote in the panel elections.|group=\"n\"}} At a by-election the voters are the current members of the D\u00e1il and Seanad.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(8) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act], and [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/69/enacted/en/html#sec69 s.69]</ref>\n\nAt a general election each panel is elected separately, the ballot listing nominees from both subpanels collated together in alphabetical order of surname. Voting is by the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), with the modification that a minimum number from each subpanel must be elected.\n\nBy-elections to fill a casual vacancy use [[instant runoff voting]]; if there are multiple vacancies on the same subpanel, separate parallel by-elections are held instead of a single multiple-seat STV by-election.<ref>1947 act s.58</ref> By-election nominations are from the same subpanel as the departed senator; no body can nominate multiple candidates.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(1)(b) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act]</ref> A by-election must be called within 180 days of a vacancy arising.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/56/enacted/en/html Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.56(1)]</ref>\n\n==In practice==\nIn practice, the vocational element is largely notional.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\"/><ref name=\"odonoghue2015\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=Martin |title='As nearly subservient' as it could be? Vocationalism and senatorial speaking behaviour in the Irish Senate 1938\u201345 |journal=Parliaments, Estates and Representation |date=17 December 2015 |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=211\u2013231 |doi=10.1080/02606755.2015.1108575}}</ref>  Because the electorate is restricted to elected representatives, political parties have a great influence in the nominations. Many panel candidates aspire to stand in the following D\u00e1il election, including ex-[[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s (D\u00e1il members) and others defeated at the preceding D\u00e1il election. Candidates from the \"outside\" (nominating bodies) panel tend to win the minimum number of seats on each panel, and even those are also mainly party based.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> In the [[2007 Seanad election|2007 election]] from the Cultural and Educational Panel, Fine Gael's Terence Slowey was eliminated despite having more votes than [[Ann Ormonde]] of Fianna F\u00e1il, because of the minimum-seat-per-subpanel rule; the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' commented on the \"arcane rules\" and Fine Gael's \"poor planning and failure to anticipate the strategy of the opposition\".<ref>{{cite news |title='Electrifying' FG fails to light up Seanad contest |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/electrifying-fg-fails-to-light-up-seanad-contest-26307351.html |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=27 July 2007 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nSeanad standing orders make no distinction between senators elected from a panel and other senators, or among different panels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing Orders relative to Public Business |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/parliamentaryBusiness/standingOrders/seanad/2017/2017-09-29_seanad-eireann-standing-orders-relative-to-public-business-2017_en.pdf |publisher=Seanad \u00c9ireann |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=2017}}</ref> For example, of the four senators on the Oireachtas joint committee on Agriculture, Food and the Marine in 2017, only one had been elected from the Agricultural Panel; two were from other panels, while the fourth was a Taoiseach's appointee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Agriculture Committee to discuss tillage and malt industries |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20171016-agriculture-committee-to-discuss-tillage-and-malt-industries/ |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=16 October 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Names Of The Members Nominated And Of The Members Elected |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2016-06-08/5/ |website=Seanad \u00c9ireann (25th Seanad) debates |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=8 June 2016}}</ref> The fact that the electorate is composed mainly of officials elected in party-political elections means the candidates they favour are also party-political rather than vocationally oriented.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\">{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Mary C. |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2016: The Election that Nobody Won |date=2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9783319408880 |pages=227\u2013253 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKVlDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227  |chapter=The Seanad Election: Second Chamber, Second Chance |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-40889-7_10}}</ref>  Since the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 recession]] there has been an increased proportion of [[independent politician]]s elected at local and D\u00e1il elections, which in turn has led to some independent senators returned from the panel elections since 2014;<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> some but not all of these have a greater focus on the functional areas of their panel. Prior to this, only a handful of independent vocational senators were elected under the 1947 act, the most recent being [[Se\u00e1n Brosnahan]] of the INTO on the Labour panel in 1973.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Week |first1=Liam |title=Electing Seanad Independents |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/letters/electing-seanad-independents-1.567425 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=9 March 2011 |language=en}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\nThe vocational aspect of the Seanad's constitution was a reflection of the influence of [[corporatism]] on [[Catholic social teaching]] of the 1930s, as outlined in the encyclical ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]''.{{#tag:ref|[[Basil Chubb]] points out that the corporatist idea was already undermined by the separation of \"Labour\" from \"Industry and Commerce\" and \"Administration\", dividing by [[social class]] rather than [[economic sector]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chubb |first1=Basil |title=The Government and Politics of Ireland |date=2014 |edition=3rd |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-89645-6 |quote=the composition of the panels, with labour separated from management, seemed actually to go contrary to those very [vocational] principles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JXDXAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |orig-year=1992 |page=197 |language=en}}</ref> |group=\"n\"}} This in turn influenced [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]'s thinking during the [[Adoption of the Constitution of Ireland|drafting of the 1937 Constitution]].<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\">{{cite book |first1=Martin |last1=O'Donoghue |title=Reforming Senates: Upper Legislative Houses in North Atlantic Small Powers 1800\u2013present |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |series=Routledge Studies in Modern History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2fS2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |isbn=9780367339685 |pages=204\u2013214 |chapter=Vocational voices or puppets of the Lower House? Irish senators, 1938\u20131948. |editor1-first=Nikolaj |editor1-last=Bijleveld |editor2-first=Colin |editor2-last=Grittner |editor3-first=David E. |editor3-last=Smith |editor4-first=Wybren |editor4-last=Verstegen}}</ref> The place of the Seanad in the new constitution was first discussed by a 1936 commission, which produced a majority and minority report, with dissenters from both.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+1936 Second House of the Oireachtas Commission recommendations<ref name=\"DL056798\">{{cite book |url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056798.pdf#page=11 |author=Second House of the Oireachtas Commission |date=November 1936 |series=Official publications |volume=P.2475 |title=Report |nopp=y |pages=Chapter III [majority report] pp.9\u201311, \u00a7\u00a717, 21\u201325; Chapter X [minority report] pp.30\u201333, \u00a7\u00a714\u201317 |location=Dublin |publisher=Stationery Office |oclc=863521464}}</ref>\n|-\n! Report \n! Fraction elected \n! Sectors of interest\n! Candidates nominated by\n! Electors\n|-\n! Majority\n| 30 of 45\n| \"National Language and Culture, the Arts, Agriculture (in all its forms) and Fisheries, Industry and Commerce, Finance, Health and Social Welfare, Foreign Affairs, Education, Law, Labour, Public Administration (including Town and Country Planning).\"\n| A committee (not necessarily TDs) elected by TDs using proportional representation\n| D\u00e1il election candidates, [[Weighted voting|weighted]] by first-preference vote\n|-\n! Minority\n| 40 of 50\n| \"(1) Farming and Fisheries, (2) Labour, (3) Industry and Commerce, (4) Education and the learned Professions.\"\n| Largely by specified functional organisations; partly by the relevant government minister.\n| TDs \n|}\n\nDe Valera's 1937 Seanad took more from the minority report.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/> The original electoral method differed in several ways from that used since 1947:<ref name=\"Byrne2013\">{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Elaine |title=Past Reforms and Present Policy: examining the Seanad Electoral(Panel Members) Act, 1947 |url=http://historyhub.ie/past-reforms-present-policy |website=History Hub |publisher=University College Dublin |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* There was a single STV ballot paper listing all candidates for all panels in order of surname.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/40/enacted/en/html#sec40 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.40(1)]</ref> The requirement for specific numbers of winners from each of five panels (and ten sub-panels) was preserved, greatly complicating the task for voters filling in the large ballot, and for eliminating candidates during the STV count process.\n* Instead of all county councillors voting directly for the panel, each council elected seven of its members to act as \"electors\".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/37/enacted/en/html#sec37 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.37]</ref>\n* The registration of nominating bodies was more closely regulated. The [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] had boycotted the [[2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]] in protest that the Cottage Tenants and Rural Works Association, a small group based in [[Ballingarry, County Limerick]], had the same status as the ICTU on the Labour panel.\n\nFor the [[Members of the 2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]], there were only 330 voters (24 of the 354 electors boycotted) which in a 43-seat ballot gave a quota of just eight votes to be elected.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> There were rumours of [[vote buying]] after the first three Seanad election and finally two convictions after the [[Members of the 5th Seanad|1944 Seanad election]].<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> The Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 was therefore repealed and replaced by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, which is still in force with minor amendments.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> Martin O'Donoghue argues that senators before the 1947 act showed a greater vocational orientation, and that, besides the corruption allegations, curbing this activism was another motivation for its changes.<ref name=\"odonoghue2015\"/>\n\nThe [[Local Government Reform Act 2014]] changed the number of councillors on each city and county council, to be somewhat more aligned with each area's population. The [[2016 Seanad election]] reflected this demographic shift in the panel electorate with an increase in the number returned from more populous urbanised council area at the expense of more rural areas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kavanagh |first1=Adrian |title=Seanad Elections 2016 \u2013 A Final Overview |url=https://adriankavanaghelections.org/2016/04/28/seanad-elections-2016-a-final-overview/ |website=Irish Elections: Geography, Facts and Analyses |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reform proposals==\nSeanad reform proposals may be divided into those requiring [[Amendments to the Constitution of Ireland|amending the Constitution of Ireland]] via [[referendum]], and those limited to amendment of statute law within the existing constitutional parameters. Those in the former group typically suggest abolishing the vocational aspect of the Seanad as ineffectual and based on outdated political thinking.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\">{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.nui.ie/elections/referendum/docs/ck1y_arCl3.pdf#page=4 |chapter=The Final Seanad Election? |page=243 |first=John |last=Coakley |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2011:  The Full Story of Ireland's Earthquake Election |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-230-34881-3 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |accessdate=6 April 2020 |quote=These three reports acknowledged the impossibility of giving effect to any meaningful form of vocational representation }}</ref> Those in the latter group typically suggest altering the nomination process and the franchise; both the 2015 [[Maurice Manning|Manning]] report and the 2018 report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group recommended that 13 panel senators continue to be elected on the current limited franchise, and the other 30 be popularly elected: all citizens over 18 could register either for one of the five panels or for one of the university constituencies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |title=Report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group |date=December 2018 |url=https://assets.gov.ie/5245/211218143426-25949b1b57ce47d5aff3eb83402fb99e.pdf#page=8 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |chapter=5. Recommendations of the Implementation Group}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1969 French constitutional referendum]] \u2014 rejected proposal to merge the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council|Economic, Social and Environmental Council]] into the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n* [[Functional constituency]] \u2014 in Hong Kong and Macao\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |title=Constitution of Ireland |pages=Articles 18\u201319 |nopp=y |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article18 |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947  |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/enacted/en/index.html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/publications/?author=seanad-eireann&topic%5B0%5D=election-results&topic%5B1%5D=elections Seanad election details since 2002], Oireachtas website\n\n{{Seanad \u00c9ireann}}\n\n[[Category:Seanad constituencies]]\n[[Category:Corporatism]]\n[[Category:Local authorities in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "A '''vocational panel''' ({{lang-ga|rolla gairm bheatha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Olltoghch\u00e1n an tSeanaid, 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/ga/election-results/seanad-general-election-2020/ |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=ga |date=3 April 2020 |quote=Foilseofar na tortha\u00ed comhairimh is d\u00e9ana\u00ed do na c\u00faig rolla gairm bheatha anseo d\u00edreach tar \u00e9is toradh gach comhairimh a fh\u00f3gairt.}}</ref>) is any of five lists of candidates from which are elected a total of 43 of the 60{{#tag:ref|Of the other 17 senators, 6 are elected from [[University constituency|university constituencies]] and [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|11 are appointed]] by the [[Taoiseach]] ([[prime minister]]).|group=\"n\"}} senators in [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], the [[upper house]] of the [[Oireachtas]] ([[parliament]]) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. Each panel corresponds to a grouping of \"interests and services\" ([[profession]]s or [[vocation]]s) of which candidates are required to have \"knowledge and practical experience\". The panels are nominated partly by Oireachtas members and partly by vocational organisations. From each panel, between five and eleven senators are [[Indirect election|elected indirectly]], by Oireachtas members and [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|local councillors]], using the [[single transferable vote]]. The broad requirements are specified by Article 18 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and the implementation details by [[acts of the Oireachtas]], principally the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, and associated [[statutory instrument]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement, Amendments, SIs made under the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/isbc/1947_42.html |website=Irish Statute Book |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interests and services, and subpanels==\nArticle 18.7.1\u00b0 of the Constitution defines the five panels and specifies that each shall elect between five and eleven senators. The 1947 act defines the numbers of senators to be elected from each of the panels, and also provides for the division of each panel into two sub-panels: the nominating bodies sub-panel and the Oireachtas sub-panel, with a minimum number from each sub-panel. The number of nominations any one body can make depends on both the number of bodies registered for the panel, and the number of senators elected from it.<ref name=\"maxperbody\"/>\t \n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Senate vocational panels\n!rowspan=2|Panel\n!colspan=2|Senators\n!colspan=2|Nominating bodies (as of 2020)\n!rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|\"Interests and services\" represented<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/3/enacted/en/html#sec3 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.3]</ref>\n|-\n!Total  !!Min. per<br/>sub-panel\n!Number<ref>{{cite web |title=Register of Nominating Bodies as revised at the annual revision and signed by the Seanad Returning Officer in pursuance of section 19 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended. |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/nominatingBodies/seanad/2019/2019-07-24_register-of-nominating-bodies-2019_en.pdf |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n!Max nominees<br/>per body<ref name=\"maxperbody\">[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/7/enacted/en/html s.26(2) of the 1947 act as amended by s.7 of the 1954 act]</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Administrative Panel|Administrative]]\n| 7  || 3\n| 20 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Public administration and social services, including voluntary social activities\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Agricultural Panel|Agricultural]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 10 || 2\n|align=\"left\"| \"Agriculture and allied interests, and fisheries\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cultural and Educational Panel|Cultural and Educational]]\n| 5  || 2\n| 34 || 1 \n|align=\"left\"| \"The national language {{bracket|i.e. [[Irish language|Irish]]}} and culture, literature, art, education\" and \"such [[profession]]al interests as may be defined by law\", namely \"law\" and \"medicine, including surgery, dentistry, veterinary medicine, and pharmaceutical chemistry\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Industrial and Commercial Panel|Industrial and Commercial]]\n| 9  || 3\n| 47 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Industry and commerce, including banking, finance, accountancy, engineering, and architecture\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Labour Panel|Labour]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 2  || 7\n|align=\"left\"| \"Labour, whether [[trade union|organised]] or unorganised\"\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Total\n| 43  || \u2014\n| 113 || \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Nominations==\nCandidates must be Irish citizens over the age of 21.  They can be nominated in two ways: by four members of Oireachtas (the new D\u00e1il or the outgoing Seanad) or by a \"nominating body\", to form respectively the Oireachtas (\"inside\") subpanel and Nominating bodies (\"outside\") subpanel.\n\n===Nominating bodies===\nA nominating body for a panel is a organisation whose work or members relates to one or more of the interests on the panel; for example, the [[Irish Congress of Trade Unions]] (ICTU) can nominate in the Labour panel, and the [[Royal Irish Academy]] in the Cultural and Education panel. Bodies must be [[non-profit]] within minimum [[governance]] standards.<ref name=\"act1947s8\">[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/8/enacted/en/html#sec8 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, s.8]</ref> The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad maintains the register of nominating bodies, published annually in ''[[Iris Oifigi\u00fail]]''. Bodies refused registration can appeal to a board comprising the [[Ceann Comhairle]] and [[Cathaoirleach]], their deputies, and a senior judge. A body cannot be registered on two panels;<ref name=\"act1947s8\"/> thus the [[Royal Dublin Society]] is on the Agricultural panel but not the Cultural and Educational panel. A body and an affiliate may not be registered on the same panel, but may be registered on different ones; for example the ICTU-affiliated [[Irish National Teachers' Organisation]] (INTO) is on the Cultural and Educational panel.\n\n===Knowledge and practical experience===\nThere is no statutory definition of what constitutes a sufficient degree of \"knowledge and practical experience\" of an interest or service to be eligible for nomination to the relevant panel.<ref name=\"groves2018\">{{cite web |last1=Groves |first1=Martin |title=Third Meeting |nopp=y |url=https://assets.gov.ie/3593/301118151408-17c7dc50bc56471da257862ca08cdf67.pdf#page=5 |editor=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |accessdate=5 April 2020 |page=Appendix: Presentation |date=12 June 2018}}</ref> The question is decided by the [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad, but may be be referred by him, or appealed by the candidate, to a judge of the [[High Court]] appointed as \"judicial referee\".<ref name=\"judicialreferee\">1947 act \u00a7\u00a736(2)(b)(ii), 38</ref> No further [[judicial review]] is permitted.<ref name=\"judicialreferee\"/> In 2018 clerk Martin Groves said that \"legislative guidelines would be of assistance to the returning officer and, I am sure, to candidates also\".<ref name=\"groves2018\"/> Before the [[Members of the 12th Seanad|1969 Seanad election]], outgoing Labour-panel senators [[John Ormonde]] and [[S\u00e9amus Dolan]] sought a pre-emptive High Court declaration that they were qualified, being members of a union (the INTO) affiliated to the ICTU.<ref name=\"it19690709\">{{cite news |title=Outgoing Senators Seek Declaration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0709/Pg011.html#Ar01100 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=9 July 1969 |page=11}}</ref> The Seanad clerk, Se\u00e1n MacGabhann, argued that as the INTO was itself a nominating body on the Cultural and Educational Panel, that was the panel on which they would be qualified.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> Justice [[Denis Pringle]] ruling in favour the plaintiffs, stated that it did not matter if they were better qualified for a different panel, and that, as regards the Labour Panel, while merely being in a union was insufficient, a candidate did not require \"specialised\" knowledge, and the plaintiff's testimony had established their qualifications.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senators win in election action|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0710/Pg007.html#Ar00704 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=10 July 1969 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=\"groves2018\"/> MacGabhann commented that, while an application form with detailed evidence similar to the plaintiffs' testimony might have satisfied him, a form simply making a bare assertion of knowledge and practical experience would not.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> In 2014, [[Fine Gael]] minister [[Heather Humphreys]] nominated John McNulty to the board of the [[Irish Museum of Modern Art]] (IMMA) shortly before Fine Gael nominated him to [[Gerard Craughwell#John McNulty|a by-election]] on the Oireachtas subpanel of the Cultural and Educational Panel. The IMMA nomination was seen as an attempt to bolster McNulty's tenuous qualifications, and the ensuing controversy impelled him to withdraw his candidacy.{{#tag:ref|His name remained from the ballot paper, but he urged electors not to vote for him.<ref name=\"mcgee2014/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=\"mcgee2014\">{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=Harry |title=Why is the John McNulty affair so important? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/why-is-the-john-mcnulty-affair-so-important-1.1951624 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=4 October 2014 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[2020 Seanad election]], Paul Hayes was excluded from the Agricultural panel on the basis that, although he had the required \"knowledge\" of fishing, he lacked \"practical experience\"; Hayes suggested that with more time he could have supplied sufficient documentation to support his case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Mahony |first1=Kieran |title=Hayes disappointed as Seanad nomination bids fail |url=https://www.southernstar.ie/news/hayes-disappointed-as-seanad-nomination-bids-fail-4202457 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Southern Star |date=25 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===<!-- [[Completion of panels]] redirects here-->Completion of panels===\nThe \"completion of panels\" occurs in public on a specified date after nominations close, when the clerk of the Seanad, assisted by the judicial referee, excludes invalid nomination papers and unqualified nominees, and allows candidates nominated on multiple panels or subpanels to select which one to go forward on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.36 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/36/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> This creates a list of provisional subpanels. The minimum number of nominees for each subpanel is two plus the maximum number to be elected from the subpanel. If there are too few candidates on a provisional subpanel, the [[Taoiseach]] must nominate extra candidates to complete the panel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.37 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/37/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[21st Seanad|1997 Seanad election]], [[Bertie Ahern]] was obliged to nominate four candidates across three Oireachtas sub-panels, none of whom polled well in the ensuing election.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Coakley |first1=John |last2=Manning |first2=Maurice |editor-last1=Marsh |editor-first1=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 1997 |chapter=The Senate Elections |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-96854-9 |page=203 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwDFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA203 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|appointed directly to the Seanad]] must be by a Taoiseach elected after a [[D\u00e1il election results|D\u00e1il general election]], nomination of candidates to complete a panel may be by an ''acting'' Taoiseach. For example, in 2020 [[Leo Varadkar]] was acting Taoiseach after [[2020 Irish general election|the D\u00e1il election]]; in [[2020 Irish Seanad election|the ensuing Seanad election]], Oireachtas members only nominated eight candidates to their subpanel of the Labour panel, so Varadkar nominated one more to bring the total up to the minimum of nine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panels of candidates prepared by the Seanad Returning Officer pursuant to Section 43 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954. |journal=Iris Oifigi\u00fail |date=10 March 2020 |issue=20A [Supplement] |page=6 |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/electoralRoll/seanad/2020/2020-03-10_seanad-general-election-2020-panels-of-candidates_en.pdf#page=6}}; {{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=FG\u2019s Mary Seery Kearney added to ticket to contest Seanad election |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fg-s-mary-seery-kearney-added-to-ticket-to-contest-seanad-election-1.4198771 |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voting==\nIn all panel elections [[postal voting]] is used. The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad is the [[returning officer]] of the count, during which each ballot is given the value of 1,000 to aid the transfer of fractions of votes. The [[electoral college]] is the same for all of the vocational panels but varies between general and [[by-election]]s. \n\nAt a Seanad general election the voters are members of [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|city and county councils]], the newly elected D\u00e1il and the outgoing Seanad; {{as of|2020|lc=y}} these number 949, 160, and 60 respectively, discounting any vacancies.{{#tag:ref|Typically, some local councillors and members of the old Seanad will have just been elected to the new D\u00e1il, vacating their former seats. In the case of a senator appointed by a Taoiseach, the outgoing acting Taoiseach will nominate a replacement in time for the panel election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=Former Labour TDs to compete for Seanad seats Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in in competition with outgoing senators for nomination |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/former-labour-tds-to-compete-for-seanad-seats-1.2571697 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> Typically, local councils likewise co-opt replacements in time,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Rachel |title=Rush to fill vacant seats created by councillors elected to D\u00e1il |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2016/0314/Pg002.html#Ar00203 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irush Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> but no by-elections are held to replace outgoing panel or university senators.  Before the 2003 abolition of the [[dual mandate]], one could be both an Oireachtas member and a local councillor, but would only get one vote in the panel elections.|group=\"n\"}} At a by-election the voters are the current members of the D\u00e1il and Seanad.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(8) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act], and [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/69/enacted/en/html#sec69 s.69]</ref>\n\nAt a general election each panel is elected separately, the ballot listing nominees from both subpanels collated together in alphabetical order of surname. Voting is by the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), with the modification that a minimum number from each subpanel must be elected.\n\nBy-elections to fill a casual vacancy use [[instant runoff voting]]; if there are multiple vacancies on the same subpanel, separate parallel by-elections are held instead of a single multiple-seat STV by-election.<ref>1947 act s.58</ref> By-election nominations are from the same subpanel as the departed senator; no body can nominate multiple candidates.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(1)(b) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act]</ref> A by-election must be called within 180 days of a vacancy arising.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/56/enacted/en/html Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.56(1)]</ref>\n\n==In practice==\nIn practice, the vocational element is largely notional.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\"/><ref name=\"odonoghue2015\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=Martin |title='As nearly subservient' as it could be? Vocationalism and senatorial speaking behaviour in the Irish Senate 1938\u201345 |journal=Parliaments, Estates and Representation |date=17 December 2015 |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=211\u2013231 |doi=10.1080/02606755.2015.1108575}}</ref>  Because the electorate is restricted to elected representatives, political parties have a great influence in the nominations. Many panel candidates aspire to stand in the following D\u00e1il election, including ex-[[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s (D\u00e1il members) and others defeated at the preceding D\u00e1il election. Candidates from the \"outside\" (nominating bodies) panel tend to win the minimum number of seats on each panel, and even those are also mainly party based.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> In the [[2007 Seanad election|2007 election]] from the Cultural and Educational Panel, Fine Gael's Terence Slowey was eliminated despite having more votes than [[Ann Ormonde]] of Fianna F\u00e1il, because of the minimum-seat-per-subpanel rule; the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' commented on the \"arcane rules\" and Fine Gael's \"poor planning and failure to anticipate the strategy of the opposition\".<ref>{{cite news |title='Electrifying' FG fails to light up Seanad contest |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/electrifying-fg-fails-to-light-up-seanad-contest-26307351.html |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Irish Independent |date=27 July 2007 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nSeanad standing orders make no distinction between senators elected from a panel and other senators, or among different panels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing Orders relative to Public Business |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/parliamentaryBusiness/standingOrders/seanad/2017/2017-09-29_seanad-eireann-standing-orders-relative-to-public-business-2017_en.pdf |publisher=Seanad \u00c9ireann |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=2017}}</ref> For example, of the four senators on the Oireachtas joint committee on Agriculture, Food and the Marine in 2017, only one had been elected from the Agricultural Panel; two were from other panels, while the fourth was a Taoiseach's appointee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Agriculture Committee to discuss tillage and malt industries |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20171016-agriculture-committee-to-discuss-tillage-and-malt-industries/ |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=16 October 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Names Of The Members Nominated And Of The Members Elected |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2016-06-08/5/ |website=Seanad \u00c9ireann (25th Seanad) debates |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=8 June 2016}}</ref> The fact that the electorate is composed mainly of officials elected in party-political elections means the candidates they favour are also party-political rather than vocationally oriented.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\">{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Mary C. |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2016: The Election that Nobody Won |date=2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9783319408880 |pages=227\u2013253 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKVlDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227  |chapter=The Seanad Election: Second Chamber, Second Chance |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-40889-7_10}}</ref>  Since the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 recession]] there has been an increased proportion of [[independent politician]]s elected at local and D\u00e1il elections, which in turn has led to some independent senators returned from the panel elections since 2014;<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> some but not all of these have a greater focus on the functional areas of their panel. Prior to this, only a handful of independent vocational senators were elected under the 1947 act, the most recent being [[Se\u00e1n Brosnahan]] of the INTO on the Labour panel in 1973.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Week |first1=Liam |title=Electing Seanad Independents |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/letters/electing-seanad-independents-1.567425 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=9 March 2011 |language=en}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\nThe vocational aspect of the Seanad's constitution was a reflection of the influence of [[corporatism]] on [[Catholic social teaching]] of the 1930s, as outlined in the encyclical ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]''.{{#tag:ref|[[Basil Chubb]] points out that the corporatist idea was already undermined by the separation of \"Labour\" from \"Industry and Commerce\" and \"Administration\", dividing by [[social class]] rather than [[economic sector]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chubb |first1=Basil |title=The Government and Politics of Ireland |date=2014 |edition=3rd |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-89645-6 |quote=the composition of the panels, with labour separated from management, seemed actually to go contrary to those very [vocational] principles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JXDXAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |orig-year=1992 |page=197 |language=en}}</ref> |group=\"n\"}} This in turn influenced [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]'s thinking during the [[Adoption of the Constitution of Ireland|drafting of the 1937 Constitution]].<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\">{{cite book |first1=Martin |last1=O'Donoghue |title=Reforming Senates: Upper Legislative Houses in North Atlantic Small Powers 1800\u2013present |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |series=Routledge Studies in Modern History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2fS2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |isbn=9780367339685 |pages=204\u2013214 |chapter=Vocational voices or puppets of the Lower House? Irish senators, 1938\u20131948. |editor1-first=Nikolaj |editor1-last=Bijleveld |editor2-first=Colin |editor2-last=Grittner |editor3-first=David E. |editor3-last=Smith |editor4-first=Wybren |editor4-last=Verstegen}}</ref> The place of the Seanad in the new constitution was first discussed by a 1936 commission, which produced a majority and minority report, with dissenters from both.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+1936 Second House of the Oireachtas Commission recommendations<ref name=\"DL056798\">{{cite book |url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056798.pdf#page=11 |author=Second House of the Oireachtas Commission |date=November 1936 |series=Official publications |volume=P.2475 |title=Report |nopp=y |pages=Chapter III [majority report] pp.9\u201311, \u00a7\u00a717, 21\u201325; Chapter X [minority report] pp.30\u201333, \u00a7\u00a714\u201317 |location=Dublin |publisher=Stationery Office |oclc=863521464}}</ref>\n|-\n! Report \n! Fraction elected \n! Sectors of interest\n! Candidates nominated by\n! Electors\n|-\n! Majority\n| 30 of 45\n| \"National Language and Culture, the Arts, Agriculture (in all its forms) and Fisheries, Industry and Commerce, Finance, Health and Social Welfare, Foreign Affairs, Education, Law, Labour, Public Administration (including Town and Country Planning).\"\n| A committee (not necessarily TDs) elected by TDs using proportional representation\n| D\u00e1il election candidates, [[Weighted voting|weighted]] by first-preference vote\n|-\n! Minority\n| 40 of 50\n| \"(1) Farming and Fisheries, (2) Labour, (3) Industry and Commerce, (4) Education and the learned Professions.\"\n| Largely by specified functional organisations; partly by the relevant government minister.\n| TDs \n|}\n\nDe Valera's 1937 Seanad took more from the minority report.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/> The original electoral method differed in several ways from that used since 1947:<ref name=\"Byrne2013\">{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Elaine |title=Past Reforms and Present Policy: examining the Seanad Electoral(Panel Members) Act, 1947 |url=http://historyhub.ie/past-reforms-present-policy |website=History Hub |publisher=University College Dublin |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* There was a single STV ballot paper listing all candidates for all panels in order of surname.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/40/enacted/en/html#sec40 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.40(1)]</ref> The requirement for specific numbers of winners from each of five panels (and ten sub-panels) was preserved, greatly complicating the task for voters filling in the large ballot, and for eliminating candidates during the STV count process.\n* Instead of all county councillors voting directly for the panel, each council elected seven of its members to act as \"electors\".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/37/enacted/en/html#sec37 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.37]</ref>\n* The registration of nominating bodies was more closely regulated. The [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] had boycotted the [[2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]] in protest that the Cottage Tenants and Rural Works Association, a small group based in [[Ballingarry, County Limerick]], had the same status as the ICTU on the Labour panel.\n\nFor the [[Members of the 2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]], there were only 330 voters (24 of the 354 electors boycotted) which in a 43-seat ballot gave a quota of just eight votes to be elected.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> There were rumours of [[vote buying]] after the first three Seanad election and finally two convictions after the [[Members of the 5th Seanad|1944 Seanad election]].<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> The Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 was therefore repealed and replaced by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, which is still in force with minor amendments.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> Martin O'Donoghue argues that senators before the 1947 act showed a greater vocational orientation, and that, besides the corruption allegations, curbing this activism was another motivation for its changes.<ref name=\"odonoghue2015\"/>\n\nThe [[Local Government Reform Act 2014]] changed the number of councillors on each city and county council, to be somewhat more aligned with each area's population. The [[2016 Seanad election]] reflected this demographic shift in the panel electorate with an increase in the number returned from more populous urbanised council area at the expense of more rural areas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kavanagh |first1=Adrian |title=Seanad Elections 2016 \u2013 A Final Overview |url=https://adriankavanaghelections.org/2016/04/28/seanad-elections-2016-a-final-overview/ |website=Irish Elections: Geography, Facts and Analyses |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reform proposals==\nSeanad reform proposals may be divided into those requiring [[Amendments to the Constitution of Ireland|amending the Constitution of Ireland]] via [[referendum]], and those limited to amendment of statute law within the existing constitutional parameters. Those in the former group typically suggest abolishing the vocational aspect of the Seanad as ineffectual and based on outdated political thinking.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\">{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.nui.ie/elections/referendum/docs/ck1y_arCl3.pdf#page=4 |chapter=The Final Seanad Election? |page=243 |first=John |last=Coakley |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2011:  The Full Story of Ireland's Earthquake Election |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-230-34881-3 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |accessdate=6 April 2020 |quote=These three reports acknowledged the impossibility of giving effect to any meaningful form of vocational representation }}</ref> Those in the latter group typically suggest altering the nomination process and the franchise; both the 2015 [[Maurice Manning|Manning]] report and the 2018 report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group recommended that 13 panel senators continue to be elected on the current limited franchise, and the other 30 be popularly elected: all citizens over 18 could register either for one of the five panels or for one of the university constituencies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |title=Report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group |date=December 2018 |url=https://assets.gov.ie/5245/211218143426-25949b1b57ce47d5aff3eb83402fb99e.pdf#page=8 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |chapter=5. Recommendations of the Implementation Group}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1969 French constitutional referendum]] \u2014 rejected proposal to merge the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council|Economic, Social and Environmental Council]] into the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n* [[Functional constituency]] \u2014 in Hong Kong and Macao\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |title=Constitution of Ireland |pages=Articles 18\u201319 |nopp=y |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article18 |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947  |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/enacted/en/index.html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/publications/?author=seanad-eireann&topic%5B0%5D=election-results&topic%5B1%5D=elections Seanad election details since 2002], Oireachtas website\n\n{{Seanad \u00c9ireann}}\n\n[[Category:Seanad constituencies]]\n[[Category:Corporatism]]\n[[Category:Local authorities in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Jnestorius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCompletion of panels:appointments directly to the Seanad", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vocational_panel"}
{"title_page": "Tetragnatha", "text_new": "{{Short description| Genus of spiders}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{Fossil range| Palaeogene| Present}}\n| taxon = Tetragnatha\n| image = Tetragnatha.extensa.female.jpg\n| image_caption = female ''T. extensa''\n| authority = [[Pierre Andr\u00e9 Latreille|Latreille]], 1804<ref name=NMBE />\n| type_species = ''[[Tetragnatha extensa|T. extensa]]''\n| type_species_authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = 323, [[#Species|see text]]\n| synonyms = \n*''Arundognatha'' <small>Wiehle, 1963</small><ref name=Levi1981>{{cite journal| last=Levi| first=H. W.| year=1981| title=The American orb-weaver genera ''Dolichognatha'' and ''Tetragnatha'' north of Mexico (Araneae: Araneidae, Tetragnathinae)| journal=Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology| volume=149| page=282}}</ref>\n*''Eucta'' <small>[[Eug\u00e8ne Simon|Simon]], 1881</small><ref name=Levi1981 />\n*''Prionolaema'' <small>Simon, 1894</small><ref name=Dimi2008>{{cite journal| last=Dimitrov| first=D.| last2=\u00c1lvarez-Padilla| first2=F.| last3=Hormiga| first3=G.| year=2008| title=Until dirt do us apart: On the unremarkable palp morphology of the spider ''Sternospina concretipalpis'' Schmidt & Krause, 1993, with comments on the genus ''Prionolaema'' Simon, 1894 (Araneae, Tetragnathidae)| journal=Zootaxa| volume=1698| page=51}}</ref>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=NMBE />\n}}\n'''''Tetragnatha''''' is a [[genus]] of [[Tetragnathidae|long-jawed orb-weavers]] found all over the world. It was first described by [[Pierre Andr\u00e9 Latreille]] in 1804,<ref name=Latr1804>{{cite journal| last=Latreille| first=P. A.| year=1804| title=Tableau methodique des Insectes| journal=Nouveau Dictionnaire d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris| pages=129\u2013295| volume=24| author-link=Pierre_Andr\u00e9_Latreille}}</ref> and it contains hundreds of species. Most occur in the [[tropics]] and [[subtropics]], and many can run over water. They are commonly called ''stretch spiders'' in reference to their elongated body form and their ability to hide on blades of [[grass]] or similar elongated substrates by stretching their front [[arthropod leg|legs]] forward and the others behind them. The name ''Tetragnatha'' is derived from Greek, ''tetra-'' a [[numerical prefix]] referring to [[four (number)|four]] and ''gnatha'' meaning \"[[jaw]]\". On the Hawaiian islands, a shift of cursorial behavior occurred long ago, when their ancestors first arrived on the island chain.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gillespie |first1=R.G. |last2=Croom |first2=H.B. |last3=Palumbi |first3=S.R. |authorlink3=Stephen R. Palumbi |year=1994 |title=Multiple origins of a spider radiation in Hawaii |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]] |volume=91 |pages=2290\u20132294 |doi=10.1073/pnas.91.6.2290 |pmid=8134390 |issue=6 |pmc=43356}}</ref>\n\nOne of the biggest and most common species is ''[[Tetragnatha extensa|T. extensa]]'', which has a [[holarctic]] distribution. It can be found near lakes, river banks or swamps.<ref name=\"Habitate Spinnen\">{{cite book |last1=H\u00e4nggi |first1=Ambros |last2=St\u00f6ckli |first2=Edi |last3=Nentwig |first3=Wolfgang |year=1995 |title=Lebensr\u00e4ume Mitteleurop\u00e4ischer Spinnen |publisher=Miscellanea Faunistica Helvetiae \u2013 Centre suisse de cartographie de la faune, Neuchatel |isbn=2-88414-008-5}}</ref> Large numbers of individuals can often be found in reeds, tall grass, and around minor trees and shrubs.\n\n==Species==\n{{as of|2019|11}} it contains 323 species and ten subspecies, found all over the world, including [[Greenland]]:<ref name=NMBE>{{cite web| title=Gen. Tetragnatha Latreille, 1804| website=World Spider Catalog Version 20.0| accessdate=2019-12-01| year=2019| publisher=Natural History Museum Bern| url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/3311| doi=10.24436/2}}</ref>\n*''[[Tetragnatha acuta|T. acuta]]'' <small>Gillespie, 1992</small> \u2013 [[Hawaii]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha aenea|T. aenea]]'' <small>Cantor, 1842</small> \u2013 [[China]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha aetherea|T. aetherea]]'' <small>([[Eug\u00e8ne Simon|Simon]], 1894)</small> \u2013 [[Venezuela]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha albida|T. albida]]'' <small>Gillespie, 1994</small> \u2013 Hawaii\n*''[[Tetragnatha americana|T. americana]]'' <small>Simon, 1905</small> \u2013 [[Chile]], [[Argentina]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha amoena|T. amoena]]'' <small>Okuma, 1987</small> \u2013 New Guinea\n*''[[Tetragnatha anamitica|T. anamitica]]'' <small>[[Charles Athanase Walckenaer|Walckenaer]], 1841</small> \u2013 [[Vietnam]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha andamanensis|T. andamanensis]]'' <small>[[B. K. Tikader|Tikader]], 1977</small> \u2013 [[India]] (Andaman Is.), [[Bangladesh]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha andonea|T. andonea]]'' <small>Lawrence, 1927</small> \u2013 [[Namibia]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha angolaensis|T. angolaensis]]'' <small>Okuma & Dippenaar-Schoeman, 1988</small> \u2013 [[Angola]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha anguilla|T. anguilla]]'' <small>[[Tamerlan Thorell|Thorell]], 1877</small> \u2013 [[Indonesia]] ([[Java]], [[Sulawesi]]), New Guinea, [[Australia]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha angulata|T. angulata]]'' <small>[[Henry Roughton Hogg|Hogg]], 1914</small> \u2013 Australia ([[Western Australia]])\n*''[[Tetragnatha anuenue|T. anuenue]]'' <small>Gillespie, 2002</small> \u2013 Hawaii\n*''[[Tetragnatha argentinensis|T. argentinensis]]'' <small>[[C\u00e2ndido Firmino de Mello-Leit\u00e3o|Mello-Leit\u00e3o]], 1931</small> \u2013 Argentina\n*''[[Tetragnatha argyroides|T. argyroides]]'' <small>Mello-Leit\u00e3o, 1945</small> \u2013 Argentina\n*''[[Tetragnatha armata|T. armata]]'' <small>[[Ferdinand Karsch|Karsch]], 1892</small> \u2013 [[Sri Lanka]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha atriceps|T. atriceps]]'' <small>[[Nathan Banks|Banks]], 1898</small> \u2013 [[Mexico]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha atristernis|T. atristernis]]'' <small>[[Embrik Strand|Strand]], 1913</small> \u2013 [[Central Africa]]\n*''[[Tetragnatha australis|T. australis]]'' <small>(Mello-L