 by the [[Swedish Armed Forces]] for familiarization training, as well as a similar number of AKMs, but they are not issued to combat units.<ref>{{cite web |author=Henrik Svensk |url=http://www.soldf.com/utlvap.html |title=M16 M16A2 Kalashnikov AK-47 \u2013 Utl\u00e4ndska Vapensatsen |publisher=SoldF.com |language=Swedish |accessdate=13 July 2014|quote=The foreign weapons kit was purchased in 1986 to give personnel in the Armed Forces the opportunity to get to know the weapons that usually show up in war and crisis situations|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410075842/https://www.soldf.com/utlvap.html |archivedate=10 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Ak 4]] and [[Ak 5]] rifles are used by [[List of equipment of the Swedish Army#Small arms|Swedish Army]].\n* {{flag|Taiwan}} Type 65, 85 and 91 Taiwanese Assault rifles modeled after the M16A2.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.militaryfactory.com/smallarms/detail.asp |title=Colt M16A2 Assault Rifle|website=Military Factory |accessdate= 23 November 2014 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141112220614/http://www.militaryfactory.com/smallarms/detail.asp |archivedate= 12 November 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Thailand}}<ref name=ewen2005 /> M16A1/A2/A4.\n* {{flag|Tunisia}}<ref name=ewen2005 /> M16A2/A4.\n* {{flag|Turkey}}<ref name=ewen2005 /> M16A1/A2/A4.\n* {{flag|Uganda}}<ref name=ewen2005 />\n* {{flag|United Arab Emirates}}<ref name=ewen2005 />\n* {{flag|United Kingdom}}: One of first military customers as UK purchased first AR-15s to be used in jungle warfare in [[Indonesia-Malaysia confrontation]].{{sfn|McNab|2002|p=243}} The [[Colt Canada C7 rifle#C8|Colt Canada C8]] (L119A1/L119A2) variant is used by [[Royal Military Police]] Close Protection Units,<ref>{{cite web  |title=Royal Military Police train for close protection |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/royal-military-police-train-for-close-protection |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |date=7 August 2012 |access-date=20 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019095153/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/royal-military-police-train-for-close-protection |archive-date=19 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> the [[16 Air Assault Brigade#Pathfinder Group|Pathfinder Group]], [[United Kingdom Special Forces]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eliteukforces.info/special-air-service/weapons/c8.php|title=SAS Weapons \u2013 C8 SFW Carbine L119A1s|work=EliteUKForces.info|accessdate=13 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519233359/http://www.eliteukforces.info/special-air-service/weapons/c8.php|archive-date=19 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[43 Commando Fleet Protection Group Royal Marines]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ripley |first=Tim |date=4 March 2016 |title=UK Royal Marine unit ditches the SA80 for Colt C8 |url=http://www.janes.com/article/58501/uk-royal-marine-unit-ditches-the-sa80-for-colt-c8 |newspaper=[[Jane's Defence Weekly|IHS Jane's Defence Weekly]] |location=London |access-date=13 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317184342/http://www.janes.com/article/58501/uk-royal-marine-unit-ditches-the-sa80-for-colt-c8 |archivedate=17 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{flag|United States}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/factfiles/equipment/individual/m16.html |title=M-16 Rifle Fact File for the United States Army |publisher=Army.mil |accessdate=22 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825003123/http://www.army.mil/factfiles/equipment/individual/m16.html |archive-date=25 August 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Uruguay}}<ref name=ewen2005 />\n* {{flag|Vietnam}}: Obtained from [[South Vietnam]] following [[Vietnam War]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Personal firepower|first=Edward Clinton|last= Ezell|publisher=Bantam Books|year=1988|series=The Illustrated history of the Vietnam War 15|oclc=1036801376|url=https://archive.org/details/personalfirepowe00ezel|pages=152\u2013153}}</ref> Over 946,000 M16s were captured in 1975 alone.<ref>{{cite book |quote=With the fall of South Vietnam in April 1975, over 946,000 M16&nbsp;\u2014 type weapons fell into communists hands|title=The M16 (Weapon)|author1=Rottman, Gordon L. |publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1849086905 |date=20 December 2011|page=34}}</ref>\n<!--\n   Provide a verifiable source for additions to the Users list above.\n-->\n\n===Former users===\n* {{Flag|Australia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-weapons/allied_recent.htm |title=Australian weapons, Viet Nam and since |publisher=Diggerhistory.info |date=11 November 2002 |accessdate=22 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811081556/http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-weapons/allied_recent.htm |archivedate=11 August 2010 }}</ref> M16A1 introduced during the Vietnam War and replaced by the [[Steyr AUG|F88 Austeyr]] in 1989.\n* {{Flag|Croatia}}<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pinterest.com/pin/411516484682692556/|title=Members of the ZNG's 1st Brigade (\"Tiger\"), armed with an AK-74, an Anschutz .22 target rifle, and M-16A2s.|via=Pinterest}} {{youtube|3qnp_99y1MY}}{{better source|date=January 2020}}</ref> M16A2 smuggled into country in small quantities, used in [[Croatian War of Independence]] and [[Croat-Bosniak War]]{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n* {{Flag|New Zealand}}<ref name=ewen2005 /> M16; replaced in 1988 by [[Steyr AUG]], which was being replaced with a [[Lewis Machine and Tool Company#MARS-L|non-Colt M16]] variant in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2015/08/18/new-zealand-army-selects-lmt-to-produce-rifle-to-replace-steyr-aug/|title=New Zealand Army Selects LMT To Replace Steyr AUG \u2013 The Firearm Blog|date=18 August 2015|website=Thefirearmblog.com|accessdate=16 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124093242/http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2015/08/18/new-zealand-army-selects-lmt-to-produce-rifle-to-replace-steyr-aug|archive-date=24 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Laos}}: Received from the US government during the [[Vietnam War]] and [[Laotian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The War in Laos 1960\u201375|series=Men-at-Arms 217|first=Kenneth |last=Conboy|date=23 November 1989 |publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=9780850459388|page=15}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Rhodesia}}: M16A1<ref name=Moorcraft>{{cite book |title=The Rhodesian War: A Military History |last1=Moorcraft |first1=Paul L. |authorlink1=Paul Moorcraft |last2=McLaughlin |first2=Peter |authorlink2=Peter McLaughlin |date=April 2008 |origyear=1982 |location=Barnsley |publisher=[[Pen and Sword Books]] |isbn=978-1-84415-694-8}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|South Vietnam}}: 6,000 M16 and 938,000 M16A1, 1966\u20131975<ref>Walter, John, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Eq2Dnj4sDZIC&pg=PA41 Rifles of the World] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323144717/https://books.google.com/books?id=Eq2Dnj4sDZIC&pg=PA41 |date=23 March 2017 }}, Krause Publications, 2006, illustrated 3rd edition, {{ISBN|0-89689-241-7}}, p. 41</ref>\n* {{flag|Zaire}}{{sfn|Rottman|2011|p=34}}<ref name = 'FDLR'/>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Ireland.svg|23px}}{{flagicon image|StarryPlough.svg|23px}} [[Provisional IRA]] - received a number of M16s during [[The Troubles]] in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ansionnachfionn.com/2015/07/09/the-reorganisation-of-the-ira-in-the-early-1970s/|title=The Reorganisation of the IRA in the Early 1970s|date=9 July 2015|publisher=An Sionnach Fionn}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Adaptive Combat Rifle]]\n* [[List of Colt AR-15 and M16 rifle variants]]\n* [[Colt 9&nbsp;mm SMG]]\n* [[Comparison of the AK-47 and M16]]\n* [[Daewoo K2]], [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces]] (South Korea) assault rifle\n* [[List of individual weapons of the U.S. armed forces]]\n* [[M203 grenade launcher|M203 40&nbsp;mm grenade launcher]]\n* [[MSBS Radon]]\n* [[Norinco CQ]], M16 clone develope